Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. Defendant Michelle Milewski in court with attorney Zoe Plovanich.  Brittany Skye Kachingwe appeared for the State of Wisconsin.   The parties have agreed to a deferred judgment agreement.

AS TO COUNT 1:  The Defendant was advised of his constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, pled GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum to Plea Questionnaire received and filed.  The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  The Court found the Defendant guilty but WITHHELD entry of Judgment of Conviction.  The court approved the Deferred Prosecution Agreement and ordered the case transferred to Judge Ashley, Branch 33 for a Review Hearing.

AS TO COUNT 2:  On motion of the State the Court ordered Count 2 DISMISSED.  Review hearing scheduled for February 27, 2017 at 10:00 am.
